Basic introduction of text analysis in R.

Text mining or text analysis, is the process of gaining insights from large collections of unstructured data. It uses natural language processing (NLP) to transform raw (unstructured) data into a normalized, structured form suitable for machine learning (ML) algorithms. Such algorithms can be used to automate tasks such as text classification and clustering, topic modeling, document summation, sentiment analysis, and key-word extraction.

  • NLP tasks include: tokenization, lemmatization/stemming, part-of-speech tagging, language detection and identification of semantic relationships.

  • Text mining techniques includes:

    • text classification: where text is assigns to predefined categories based on its content; used to identify topics, sentiment, language, etc.

    • text extraction: named-entity-recognition extracts specific pieces of data from text (eg: keywords, prices, company names, etc.)

Preprocessing

Text data contains characters such as punctuation, stop words, etc., noise that adds little value in understanding the meaning of text but increases the complexity of the analysis. Preprocessing text involves removing this noise in order to simplify our data and analysis. Preprocessing includes the following:

  • Tokenization
  • Cleansing
  • Stemming & Lemmatization

Tokenization

The first step in text preprocessing is tokenization, which involves breaking text into meaningful elements (token). A token is a unit of analysis such as words, sequences of words (n-grams), entire sentences, symbols or other meaninful elements.

Cleansing

  • normalizing case by converting all letters to lower or upper
  • removing punctuations, numbers and white spaces
  • removing stop words, sparce terms or specific words

Stemming & Lemmatization

The goal of both stemming and lemmatization is to reduce related forms of a word to a common base form. (eg: troubled, troubles are reduced to trouble)
Documents use different forms of a word (eg: organize, organizes, organizing). Also there are families of related words with similar meanings (eg: democracy, democratic, democratization). Often it would be useful for a search for one of these words to return documents that contain another word in the set.

  • Stemming uses a more crude approach, that basically chops off letters from the end until the stem is reached. While this works well in many cases, there are many exceptions that require a more sophisticated process. As a result stemming may not result in a real word. There are 2 primary errors in stemming:
    • Over-stemming (false-positives): when 2 words are stemmed from the same root that are of different stems.
    • Under-stemming: (false-negatives): when 2 words are stemmed from the same root that are not of different stems.
  • Lemmatization considers a language’s full vocabulary and word context and converts a word to its meaningful base form (lemma). The lemma of ‘was’ is ‘be’, and ‘mice’ is ‘mouse’. Lemmatization results in a real word, but the process can be computationally expensive. Where performance is an issue such as with a large dataset, stemming may be prefered, depending on your application.

Stemming example

Here the SnowBall algorithm is used for stemming

library(SnowballC)
library(tidytext)
library(dplyr, warn.conflicts = FALSE)

txt <- c(d1 = "spaCy is great at fast natural language processing.",
         d2 = "The democratic and replublic parties have become so polarized.")

text_df <- tibble(line = 1:2, text = txt)

text_df %>%
  unnest_tokens(word, text) %>%
  mutate(stem = wordStem(word))
## # A tibble: 17 x 3

Lemmatization example

Here is an example that uses the spacyr package which provides an R wrapper around the Python spaCy package. spaCy offers access to the following functionality enabled by the R package.

  • parsing texts into tokens or sentences
  • lemmatizing tokens
  • parsing dependencies (to identify the grammatical structure of the sentence)
  • identifying, extracting, or consolidating token sequences that form named entities or noun phrases.

These are tasks used in named-entity recognition (NER), also referred as entity identification or entity extraction. NER is an information extraction (IE) technique that automatically identifies named-entities in a text and classifies them into predefined categories such as: persons, organizations, locations, time, quantities, monetary values, etc.

library("spacyr")
spacy_initialize(model = "en_core_web_sm")

# process documents and obtain a data.table
parsedtxt <- spacy_parse(txt)
parsedtxt

Document-Term Matrix

A document-term matrix or term-document matrix describes the frequency of terms that occur in a collection of documents. Many data mining tasks (eg: word frequencies, clustering, classification, association analysis) require such a matrix.

  • document-term matrix: a matrix where each word is a row and each column is a document. The number within each cell presents the number of times (frequency) the word appears in the document.

  • term-document matrix: it’s like the first but transposed, where each document is a row and each column is a word.

Read twitter data from file and create a corpus

From the last exercise Twitter data was collected using the Twitter api via the R wrapper rtweet and saved to file.

  • read the data csv data and filter on just Trump, the focus of analysis
  • build a documet corpus
# read as a tibble
twitterDf = read.csv('~/Desktop/GGU/data 104/data/candidates.csv', 
                     stringsAsFactors = FALSE)

# filter on trump tweets for analyis
trumpDf = twitterDf  %>%
    filter(is_retweet==FALSE) %>% # remove retweets
    select(screen_name, text) %>%
    filter(screen_name=='realDonaldTrump')

# build a document corpus
trumpCorpus <- Corpus(VectorSource(trumpDf$text))
trumpCorpus

Preprocessing

Using the tm package, perform transformations on the corpora to clean the text. There are generalized text cleaning activities such as normalization and stop word removal, however twitter data has additional data (eg: urls, retweets, hashtags, etc) that need to be removed.

# standard cleansing
trumpCorpus <- tm_map(trumpCorpus, tolower)            # normalize case
trumpCorpus <- tm_map(trumpCorpus, removePunctuation)  # remove punctuation
trumpCorpus <- tm_map(trumpCorpus, removeNumbers)      # remove numbers
trumpCorpus <- tm_map(trumpCorpus, stripWhitespace)    # remove white space
trumpCorpus <- tm_map(trumpCorpus, removeWords, stopwords("english")) # remove stopwords

# custom cleansing for twitter data
trumpCorpus <- tm_map(trumpCorpus, removeWords, c('t.co', 'amp')) # remove custom stopwords


# remove patterns via regular expressions
textCleaning <- function(txt){
  gsub("http[[:alnum:]]*",'', txt)
  gsub('http\\S+\\s*', '', txt) # Remove URLs
  gsub('\\b+RT', '', txt)       # Remove RT
  gsub('#\\S+', '', txt)        # Remove Hashtags
  gsub('@\\S+', '', txt)        # Remove Mentions
}
trumpCorpus <- tm_map(trumpCorpus, textCleaning)

Note: Term-document matrices tend to get very big already for normal sized data sets. Therefore function removeSparseTerms() can be used to remove sparse terms (i.e., terms occurring only in very few documents). Normally, this reduces the matrix dramatically without losing significant relations inherent to the matrix. The sparse argument to removeSparseTerms(), is the threshold of relative document frequency for a term, above which the term will be removed. It is a value between 0 and 1. Closer to 0 means nearly all values will be retained while closer to 1 means nearly none of the documents will be retained.

inspect (removeSparseTerms(dtm2, .85))
## <<DocumentTermMatrix (documents: 1733, terms: 1)>>

break text into tokens using tidytext

The unnest_tokens() function, part of tidytext, performs some automatic text cleaning

  • The unnest_tokens() function takes 2 arguments:
    • the name of the column where the unique word will be stored
    • the column name from the data frame containing the text
  • Converts each word in text to lowercase,
  • Punctuation is removed: eg: periods, commas etc
tidy_df <- tidy_df %>%
    unnest_tokens(word, text) %>%
    count(word) %>%
    arrange(desc(n))

Top bi-grams

A bigram is an n-gram for n=2. Here we show the top (15) 2 word phrases.

df = trumpDf %>%
  # filter out other urls, etc
  filter(!str_detect(text, 'http\\S+\\s*'),
         !str_detect(text, 'amp'),
         !str_detect(text, 't.co')) %>%
  # get bi-grams
  unnest_tokens(bigram, text, token = "ngrams", n = 2) %>%
  # separate bi-grams into different columns
  separate(bigram, c("word1", "word2"), sep = " ") 

bigrams = df  %>%
  filter(!word1 %in% stop_words$word) %>% # filter out stop words
  filter(!word2 %in% stop_words$word) %>%
  count(word1, word2, sort = TRUE) %>%
  head(15)
